{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648384"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:53:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:53:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18310"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18310"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.64,0.18,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11028"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59706"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7380"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25595"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the difference in function between the greater and lesser tuberosity of the humerus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The greater tuberosity is involved in shoulder extension, while the lesser tuberosity is involved in shoulder flexion","The greater tuberosity is responsible for internal rotation of the arm, while the lesser tuberosity is responsible for external rotation","The greater tuberosity provides attachment for the supraspinatus, infraspinatus, and teres minor muscles, while the lesser tuberosity provides attachment for the subscapularis muscle","The greater tuberosity is involved in arm abduction, while the lesser tuberosity is involved in arm adduction","The greater tuberosity stabilises the shoulder joint, while the lesser tuberosity facilitates shoulder flexion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe humerus is a long bone in the upper arm that features two prominent projections known as the greater and lesser tuberosities. These structures serve as important sites for muscle attachment, particularly for the rotator cuff muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that the \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater tuberosity provides attachment for the supraspinatus, infraspinatus, and teres minor muscles\u003C/strong\u003E, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Elesser tuberosity provides attachment for the subscapularis muscle\u003C/strong\u003E. These muscles are part of the rotator cuff, which plays a crucial role in stabilising the shoulder joint and enabling various arm movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe greater tuberosity is involved in arm abduction, while the lesser tuberosity is involved in arm adduction\u003C/strong\u003E - Both tuberosities serve as muscle attachment sites rather than directly facilitating specific movements\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe greater tuberosity is responsible for internal rotation of the arm, while the lesser tuberosity is responsible for external rotation\u003C/strong\u003E - The greater tuberosity is associated with external rotators, while the lesser tuberosity is associated with the internal rotator subscapularis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe greater tuberosity stabilises the shoulder joint, while the lesser tuberosity facilitates shoulder flexion\u003C/strong\u003E - Both tuberosities contribute to shoulder stability through muscle attachments\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe greater tuberosity is involved in shoulder extension, while the lesser tuberosity is involved in shoulder flexion\u003C/strong\u003E - These functions are not directly related to the tuberosities themselves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The greater tuberosity of the humerus serves as the attachment site for the supraspinatus, infraspinatus, and teres minor muscles, which are part of the rotator cuff.","The lesser tuberosity of the humerus serves as the attachment site for the subscapularis muscle, which is also part of the rotator cuff.","The rotator cuff muscles are responsible for stabilising the shoulder joint and facilitating various movements of the arm."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Forro SD, Munjal A, Lowe JB. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Arm Structure and Function. 2023 Jul 25. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29939618.","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59706"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18310"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59706"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T03:29:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T03:29:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11028"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","i